The FTIR spectra shown in Fig. 1d confirm the presence of different groups of N, S@C-dots. The band at 3345 cm−1 corresponds to υ (OH, NH). The band at 2830−2950 cm−1 is attributed to υ (CH). The sharp bands at 1730 and 1625 cm−1 correspond to υ (CO and /or CN) and 

                        δ (OH, NH), respectively. The bands at 1460, 1405, 1260, and 1185 cm−1 correspond to υ (CC), υ (C–S), υ (CN), and υ (CO

                        ), respectively (Mahmoud et al., 2019; Ali et al., 2021a,b;Khashaba et al., 2018; El-Wekil et al., 2019).

For the electrochemical approach, many parameters affecting the oxidation of rutin were optimized such as volume and concentration of N, S@C-dots, pH, potential scan rate, and preconcentration potential and time. Different concentrations of N, S@C-dots at fixed volume (6.0 μL) were dropped on the surface of GCE and the anodic peak currents of rutin were observed. Fig. S8A shows that the anodic peak currents of 25.0 × 10−8 M rutin were firstly increased from 0.5 to 2.5 mg mL-1 N, S@C-dots. If the film of drop-casted N, S@C-dots is too thick, this would weaken the plane structure of N, S@C-dots and would reduce the electrical conductivity between the modified electrode and rutin. As a result, 2.5 mg mL-1 of N, S@C-dots was chosen as an optimum concentration for the electro-chemical oxidation of rutin. The anodic peak currents (Ipa) of rutin tend to increase upon varying the volume from 1.5–6.0 μL (Fig. S8B). Whereas, a further increase of the N, S@C-dots casted volume resulted in deprived current compared to lower casted volumes. As a result, 6.0 μL was chosen as an optimum volume due to the formation of a fine layer over GCE, which enhances the electrochemical active surface area. At 8 μL, the anodic peak current was decreased due to the bulk loading of N, S@C-dots that constrains the movement of electrons between N, S@C-dots/GCE and rutin. The DPV technique was used to study the effect of pH on the electro-chemical oxidation of 25.0 × 10−8 M rutin using B.R. buffer in the pH range of 4.0−9.0. The results shown in Fig. S9A prove that the oxidation of rutin was affected by the change in the pH value. Upon increasing the pH from 4.0–7.0 a sharp peak was obtained with a negative shift in the anodic peak due to the participation of protons within the reaction. The highest anodic current was attained at pH 7.0, and a further increase in the pH value from 7.0–9.0 resulted in the decrease of anodic current as a result of less participation of protons. As a result, pH 7.0 was chosen as an ideal value for the electro-chemical oxidation of rutin. The plot in Fig. S9B shows a linear relationship between peak potential and pH with a regression equation of Epa (V) = -0.050 pH + 0.66 (r2 = 0.9980). The slope value of -50 mV/pH applied in Nernst equation: Ep = (0.059 m/n) pH + b, where the number of electrons and protons was indicated by m/n ratio. Using the slope with a value of 50 mV, the m/n ratio was estimated to be 0.92 which is almost equal to one, illustrating the number of protons and electrons participated within the electro-chemical oxidation of rutin at N, S@C-dots/GCE is equal. The process involves the participation of two proton/electrons, which occurs due to the conversion of catechol moiety into an ortho-quinone structure (Scheme 2
                        ). To enhance the sensitivity of the DPV method, accumulation potential and time were optimized for rutin electrochemical oxidation at N, S@C-dots/GCE. The results, shown in Fig.S10, indicated that the optimum accumulation potential and time were 0.1 V and 150 s, respectively. Cyclic voltammetry (CV) was carried out at different potential scan rates in the range of 0.05−0.35 Vs-1 in B.R. buffer (pH 7.0) at N, S@C-dots/GCE. Fig.2
                        A shows that with the increase of the scan rate, the anodic peak current tends to increase linearly with a slight shift in Epa and Epc, signifying that the electrochemical oxidation of rutin depends on the potential scan rate. Fig. 2B exhibits a linear relationship between scan rate½ (V s-1)½ and anodic currents (Ipa) with a regression equation of Ipa (μA) = 0.752 + 86.336 ν (Vs-1) (r2 = 0.9953). It is obvious from the linear relationship that the rutin underwent surface-controlled oxidation rather than diffusion-controlled oxidation.
